{{Bantu-lang-stub}}

'''Cannabis in Algeria''' is illegal.

==History==
Cannabis is believed to have been introduced to Algeria by the Arab invasions of the 9th through 12th centuries.<ref name="Nahas1992">{{cite book|author=Gabriel G. Nahas|title=Cannabis Physiopathology Epidemiology Detection|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6doGy7klT88C&pg=PA208|date=31 December 1992|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-8310-6|pages=208–}}</ref>

Cannabis use in Algeria also played a role in spreading the habit to France, following France's 1830 occupation of Algeria.<ref name="Rainford2010">{{cite book|author=John Rainford|title=Consuming Pleasures: Australia and the International Drug Business|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3FQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT134|date=14 May 2010|publisher=Fremantle Press|isbn=978-1-921696-73-2|pages=134–}}</ref> Dr. [[Jacques-Joseph Moreau]] observed the effects of cannabis in Algeria in the form of an edible called ''[[dawamesc]]'', and it was this drug that he introduced to Paris' [[Club des Hashischins]].<ref name="Regan2012">{{cite book|author=Ciaran Regan|title=Intoxicating Minds: How Drugs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wz9bGD0GToUC&pg=PT134|date=19 June 2012|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-53311-9|pages=134–}}</ref>

In 1854, John Morell wrote of his travels in Algeria:
<blockquote>''In Algeria they apply the names of kif, of hachich, and sometimes of tekrouri, to the extremity of the stem of the hemp, including the leaves, the flowers, and the seed, sometimes smoked by the natives in very diminutive pipes. These smokers are mostly inhabitants of the towns and villages, and are rarely met with among the Bedouins.''<ref name="Morell1854">{{cite book|author=John Reynell Morell|title=Algeria: The Topography and History, Political, Social, and Natural, of French Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=REVCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA108|year=1854|publisher=N. Cooke|pages=108–}}</ref></blockquote>

