{{Infobox flag
| Name = Shan State
| Image = Flag of the Shan State.svg
| Symbol = {{FIAV|normal}}
| Proportion = 1:2
| Adoption = 12 February 1947
| Design = A horizontal triband of yellow, green and red; charged with a large white circle at the centre.
}}

The '''flag of [[Shan State]]''' was adopted as one of the provisions of the [[Panglong Agreement]] signed on 12 February 1947, which served as the most important stepping stone towards the independence of [[Myanmar]].

The flag is a horizontal triband of yellow, green and red, with a white circle in the centre. Yellow represents [[Buddhism]], which is practiced by a majority of the [[Shan people]], green represents the rich agricultural land in Shan State, red represents the bravery of the Shan people and the white circle represents the moon, which symbolizes the Shan people's hopes for peace and stability.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sca-uk.org.uk/?about-shan#shan_culture|title=About Shan|publisher=Shan Culture Association - UK|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref> Other interpretations suggest that the yellow represents the colour of a [[Bhikkhu|monk's]] robe or a rice field during harvest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shan State (Myanmar) |url=https://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/mm-shan.html |website=www.crwflags.com |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>

