{{Redirect|WDCS|the former FM radio station in Maine|WJBQ}} {{Use British English|date=January 2012}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}} {{Infobox organization | logo =WDC Logo H D CMYK.jpg | type = Conservation Charity (Registered Charity No. 1014705) | key_people = Chris Butler-Stroud (Chief Executive) | footnotes = | name = Whale and Dolphin Conservation (WDC) | founded_date = 1987 | founder = | location = Brookfield House, 38 St Paul Street, Chippenham, Wiltshire SN15 1LJ, UK<ref>[http://uk.whales.org/contact-us WDC Contact Information]</ref> | origins = | area_served = Worldwide | product = | focus = | method = Research, Conservation, Lobbying and Negotiation. | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsib = | owner = | homepage = http://whales.org/ | dissolved = }}
'''Whale and Dolphin Conservation''' ('''WDC''') is a wildlife charity that is dedicated solely to the worldwide conservation and welfare of all [[whales]], [[dolphins]] and [[porpoises]] ([[cetaceans]]).<ref>[http://whales.org/ WDC Homepage]</ref> WDC is a founding partner of the [[Convention on Migratory Species]] (CMS, also known as the [[Bonn Convention]]), which is part of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]]. The organization also develops regional protection agreements and conventions and closely cooperates with the [[orca]] (killer whale) research station [[OrcaLab]] in British Columbia, Canada.
==History== WDC was established in 1987, its headquarters are in [[Chippenham]] in Wiltshire, UK. Until late 2012, it was known as the Whale and Dolphin Conservation Society. Today it is a leading NGO solely dedicated to the protection of cetaceans and their living environments. WDC operates worldwide with offices in [[Germany]], [[Australia]], [[Argentina]], [[Great Britain]] and the [[United States]].
==Wildlife visitor centre== The flagship Scottish Dolphin Centre is based at the mouth of the [[River Spey]] on the southern shore of the [[Moray Firth]] on the east coast of [[Scotland]].<ref>[http://www.wdcs.org/connect/wildlife_centre/index.php WDC Wildlife Centres]</ref> On the north side of the Firth lies [[Chanonry Point]] which is reputed to be one of the best spots in the UK to view [[bottlenose dolphin]] (''Tursiops truncatus'') from the land.
